Cloakfox: cap Error.stack frame count at 20 to defeat PHANTOM_ETSL.

Sannysoft / fpscanner classify a browser as PhantomJS-like when an
Error's `.stack` string contains more than 30 newline-separated
frames (PhantomJS used to ship 100+). Vanilla Firefox 146 uses
MAX_REPORTED_STACK_DEPTH = 1u << 7 = 128, so deeply-nested test
harnesses (CreepJS, sannysoft) routinely report 30+ and trip the
detector.

Setting the cap to 20 keeps Error.stack semantically useful for real
debugging while landing well below Sannysoft's >30 FAIL threshold and
matching the order of magnitude that Chrome (default 10) and
Safari (~64 capped per-error) emit. The previous JS-actor approach
(CloakfoxErrorsChild setting Error.stackTraceLimit = 10) was a no-op
because SpiderMonkey doesn't honour the V8-style stackTraceLimit
property — only this engine constant actually clamps the stack
length the page reads.

The constant is consumed by:
  - js/src/jsexn.cpp:227          (CaptureStack callsite)
  - js/src/vm/ErrorObject.cpp:1068 (ErrorObject construction)
both wrapped in JS::StackCapture(JS::MaxFrames(MAX_REPORTED_STACK_DEPTH)).

--- a/js/src/jsexn.h
+++ b/js/src/jsexn.h
@@ -38,7 +38,12 @@ UniquePtr<JSErrorReport> CopyErrorReport(JSContext* cx, JSErrorReport* report);

 // Cut off the stack if it gets too deep (most commonly for infinite recursion
 // errors).
-static const size_t MAX_REPORTED_STACK_DEPTH = 1u << 7;
+// Cloakfox: lowered from 128 to 20 so Error.stack stays under Sannysoft's
+// PHANTOM_ETSL FAIL threshold (>30 frames flags as PhantomJS-like). 20 is
+// large enough for real debugging, small enough to look like a normal
+// modern browser. Affects every site that reads `e.stack.split('\n').length`
+// — CreepJS and fpscanner-derived antibot scripts include this signal.
+static const size_t MAX_REPORTED_STACK_DEPTH = 20;

 bool CaptureStack(JSContext* cx, MutableHandleObject stack);

